Ask HN: Is the Italy of My Dreams Fact or Fiction?
text:
Hello! I'm Italian on both sides yet have never visited Italy, or any European country for that matter. [Context: I've traveled the U.S., Canada, Mexico & Caribbean extensively. Also Singapore, Hong Kong, Thailand & Seychelles]

I'll be turning 50 later this year, thus my "bucket list" is consistently dominating an ever-growing percentage of mindshare.

I'm enamored with the small villages, family-first ethos and local artisans seemingly delighted in their quest to produce the best cheese, sausage, salumi, etc. Most recently Stanley Tucci's "Searching for Italy" series leaves me searching for plane tickets.

I'd be grateful to hear if the Italy of my dreams is real vs. fantasy.

text:

Can all this complex set of knowledge collapse to some concepts that are approachable to the untrained mind in a sort of an intuitive way?

Advice for quitting startup I founded
text:
i'm leaving a startup i cofounded after 1 year because my cofounder and i have decided we're not compatible. he is the CEO, and it makes the most sense for me to be the one to step away. honestly, the last year was quite miserable with our dynamic so i'm pretty happy about it.

the question is: he doesn't want to tell our investors the real reason why i'm leaving (afraid of gossip, side picking), and he wants us to fabricate some other reason for why (he suggested saying i got burnt out, which i rejected as this is untrue and makes it look like i lack resilience, and i intend to start another company in the near future). what is the best narrative for leaving a startup you cofounded, especially if you plan to raise money for another startup in the future?
